There are 4 general economic analyses used in health care: cost minimization, 
cost-benefit, cost-effectiveness, and cost utility. In this review, we provide 
an overview of each of these analyses and examine their appropriateness and 
effectiveness in assessing critical care costs. In the intensive care unit 
setting, it is particularly important to consider the patients' quality of life 
following the treatment of critical illness and to adopt a societal perspective 
when conducting economic analyses. Therefore, of the 4 economic analyses we 
cover, we recommend the use of cost-effectiveness and cost utility analyses.

